<div class="description">
    <h3>Description</h3>

    <div class="body">
        <p>When adding a "select" element to Zend_Form and not specifying select values (Zend uses numerical indices by default), and using the auto-enabled InArray validator, the validation erroneously validates when non-numeric values are submitted.</p>

<p>This is traced back to the functionality of php's in_array with strict set by default to false.</p>

<p>For example:</p>

<pre><code>    $form-&gt;addElement('select', 'myLabel', array(
        'multioptions' =&gt; array('myOption1', 'myOption2', 'myOption3'),
        'label'      =&gt; 'User Role:',
        'required'   =&gt; true,
    ));
</code></pre>

<p>If you inject an out of bounds number, it invalidates.  However if you inject a string, it validates.  This presents a security problem if you're relying on this validation to catch malformed posts.</p>

